{{Infobox ancient site |name = Gödény-halom |native_name = |alternate_name = |image = Gödény-halom (panoráma) - panoramio.jpg |alt = |caption = Panoramic view of Gödény-halom |map_type = Hungary |map_alt = |relief = yes |location = [[Békésszentandrás]] |region = [[Hungary]] |coordinates = {{coord|46.813306|20.444658|display=inline}} |type = [[Tumulus]] |epochs = [[Neolithic]] / [[Bronze age]] }} '''Gödény-halom''' ({{lang-en|Pelican mound}}) is a [[tumulus|prehistoric mound]] situated near the village of [[Békésszentandrás]] in [[Békés County]], in the [[Southern Great Plain]] region of south-east [[Hungary]].
==Description== Gödény-halom is situated 7 kilometres away from the inner area of Békésszentandrás, close to the old road to [[Szentes]].<ref name="natty">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nemzetijelkepek.hu/onkormanyzat-bekesszentandras_en.shtml|title=Békésszentandrás (The County of Békés)|publisher=National and historical symbols of Hungary|access-date=1 March 2017}}</ref> It is in the one-time flood area of the River [[Körös|Hármas-Körös]].<ref name="natty"/> The name gödény ({{lang-en|pelican}}) refers to the fact that it was once a roosting spot for pelicans in the swampy area.<ref name="natty"/> Today, it marks the county boundaries of Békés, [[Csongrád County|Csongrád]] and [[Jász-Nagykun-Szolnok County|Szolnok]].<ref name="tajjy">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tajgazda.hu/index.php/en/our-articles/112-landscapes/319-cumanian|title=The mysterious Cumanian mounds|publisher=Tajgazda|date=27 September 2016}}</ref> Part of the northern side has been destroyed for the building of roads and a nearby dam.<ref name="natty"/>
Gödény-halom is the largest of the so-called [[Cumanian mounds]] of central Europe, and the highest prehistoric mound in Hungary with a height 12.2 metres.<ref name="locky">{{Cite book|last=Loczy|first=Dénes|year=2015|title=Landscapes and Landforms of Hungary|page=256|isbn=3319089978}}</ref> The Cumanian mounds are structures of uncertain age and origin and made by humans.<ref name="tajjy"/> It is generally thought that they were used as burial places in the Neolithic and Bronze Ages.<ref name="locky"/>
