{{Infobox writer | name = Sir Paul Vinogradoff | image = Paul Vinogradoff.jpg | caption = | birth_date = 18 November 1854 [[Adoption of the Gregorian calendar#Adoption in Eastern Europe|O.S.]] | birth_place = [[Kostroma]], [[Russian Empire]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1925|12|19|1854|11|30|df=y}} | death_place = [[Paris]], [[France]] | occupation = [[Historian]], [[Educator]], Professor of the {{Moscow University Professor|1}} | nationality = [[Russians|Russian]] (to 1918); [[British people|British]] (from 1918) | period = | genre = | subject = [[Middle Ages|Medieval Europe]] | movement = | notableworks = ''Villainage in England: Essays in English Medieval History'' | spouse = Louise Stang | children = 2 | relatives = | imagesize = 180px | influences = | influenced = | alma_mater = {{Moscow University|1875}} | education = [[Doctor of Science]] <small>(1887)</small> }} '''Sir Paul Gavrilovitch Vinogradoff''', [[British Academy|FBA]] ({{lang-ru|Па́вел Гаври́лович Виногра́дов}}, transliterated: ''Pavel Gavrilovich Vinogradov''; 18 November 1854 [[Adoption of the Gregorian calendar#Adoption in Eastern Europe|(O.S.)]]{{snd}}19 December 1925) was a Russian and British [[historian]] and [[medievalist]].
== Early life == Vinogradoff was born in [[Kostroma]] and was educated at the local [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] and [[Moscow University]], where he studied history under [[Vasily Klyuchevsky]]. After graduating in 1875, he obtained a scholarship to continue his studies in [[Berlin]], where he studied under [[Theodor Mommsen]] and [[Heinrich Brunner]].
==Career== Vinogradoff became professor of history at the [[University of Moscow]], but his zeal for the spread of education brought him into conflict with the authorities, and consequently he was obliged to leave Russia. Having settled in England, Vinogradoff brought a powerful and original mind to bear upon the social and economic conditions of early England, a subject which he had already begun to study in Moscow.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}
Vinogradoff visited Britain for the first time in 1883, working on records in the [[Public Record Office|Public Records Office]] and meeting leading English scholars such as [[Henry James Sumner Maine|Sir Henry Maine]] and [[Sir Frederick Pollock, 3rd Baronet|Sir Frederick Pollock]]. He also met [[Frederic William Maitland]], who was heavily influenced by their meeting.
Vinogradoff was elected a member of the [[American Antiquarian Society]] in 1897.<ref>[http://www.americanantiquarian.org/memberlistv American Antiquarian Society Members Directory]</ref>
In 1903 he was elected to the position of [[Corpus Professor of Jurisprudence]] at the [[University of Oxford]], and held this position until he died in 1925. He was elected a Fellow of the [[British Academy]] in 1905. He received honorary degrees from the principal universities (including [[D.C.L.]] from the [[University of Oxford]] in October 1902, in connection with the tercentenary of the [[Bodleian Library]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=University intelligence |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=8 October 1902 |page_number=4 |issue=36893| }}</ref>), was made a member of several foreign academies and was appointed honorary professor of [[history]] at Moscow.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}
Upon the death of Maitland, Vinogradoff became the literary director of the [[Selden Society]] with [[Sir Frederick Pollock, 3rd Baronet|Sir Frederick Pollock]], a position he held until 1920. During [[World War I]] he gave valuable assistance to the British Foreign Office in connection with Russian affairs.<ref name>{{EB1922|inline=y|wstitle=Vinogradoff, Paul|volume=32|page=927}}</ref> Vinogradoff was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1917,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30138|date=19 June 1917 |page=6047}}</ref> and he and his children were [[Naturalization|naturalized]] as [[British subject]]s in 1918.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30505|date=1 February 1918 |page=1547}}</ref>
In 1925, Vinogradoff traveled to [[Paris]] to receive an honorary degree; while in Paris, he developed [[pneumonia]] and died there on 19 December.
==Books== According to the [[Encyclopædia Britannica Eleventh Edition|''Encyclopædia Britannica'' Eleventh Edition]], published in 1911, Vinogradoff's ''Villainage in England'' (1892) was "perhaps the most important book written on the peasantry of the [[feudal]] age and the village community in England; it can only be compared for value with [[Frederic William Maitland|FW Maitland]]'s ''[[Domesday Book]] and Beyond''. In masterly fashion Vinogradoff here shows that the [[villein]] of [[Norman dynasty|Norman]] times was the direct descendant of the [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] freeman, and that the typical Anglo-Saxon settlement was a free community, not a manor, the position of the freeman having steadily deteriorated in the centuries just around the [[Norman Conquest]]. The status of the villein and the conditions of the manor in the 12th and 13th centuries are set forth with a legal precision and a wealth of detail which shows its author, not only as a very capable historian, but also as a brilliant and learned jurist."{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}
The article considered that almost equally valuable was Vinogradoff's essay on “Folkland” in vol.&nbsp;viii. of the ''English Historical Review'' (1893), which proved for the first time the real nature of this kind of land. Vinogradoff followed up his ''Villainage in England'' with ''The Growth of the Manor'' (1905) and ''English Society in the Eleventh Century'' (1908), works on the lines of his earlier book.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}
In ''"Outlines in Historical Jurisprudence"'' (1920–22), Vinogradoff traces the development of basic themes of jurisprudence, including marriage, property, and succession, in six different types of society: the totemistic, the tribal, the ancient city state, the medieval system of feudalism and canon law, and modern industrial society.
