[[File:Water-dropper.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Water-dropper]] [[File:Chinese hen-shaped water dropper.jpg|thumb|A hen-shaped water dropper]] A {{Nihongo|'''water-dropper'''|水滴|suiteki|lead=yes|extra={{zh|t=水滴|p=shuǐdī}}}} is a small device used in East Asian calligraphy as a container designed to hold a small amount of water. In order to make ink a few drops of water are dropped onto the surface of an [[inkstone]]. By grinding an [[inkstick|inkstick into this water on the inkstone]], particles come off and mix with the water, forming ink.
Water-droppers may be made of copper, jade or other stone, or ceramic. A water-dropper has two small holes for water and air, and is designed so that only a few drops of water can fall at one time.<ref>[http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/deta/s/suiteki.htm suiteki 水滴] {{en icon}}; aisf.or.jp, consulted on: 2012-12-31</ref>
There are a few types of water-droppers.
{| class="wikitable" width="70%" ! Type of water-dropper || [[Hanzi]] / [[Kanji]] || [[Pinyin]] || [[Romanization of Japanese|Rōmaji]] |- | Water-dropper with pouring spout and a handle || {{zh|c=水注|labels=no}} || {{transl|zh|shuǐzhù}} || {{transl|ja|suichuu}} |- | Water-droppers in diverse forms with large openings || {{zh|c=水中丞|labels=no}} || {{transl|zh|shuǐzhōngchéng }}|| {{transl|ja|suichuujou}} |- | Jar-like water-droppers with large opening || {{zh|c=水盂|labels=no}} || {{transl|zh|shuǐyú}} || {{transl|ja|suiu}} |- | Frog shaped water-dropper || {{zh|c=蟾蜍|labels=no}} || {{transl|zh|chánchú}} || {{transl|ja|senjo}} |}
